Maybe your ZkProgram or their publicInput or publicOutput is too big to fit into the limits.

You can try to run analyzeMethods() or temporarily change the publicInput or publicOutput to simple types to see where is the problem.
However , there is no error when I run  `toUpdated`  in my smart contract implementation
I see that toUpdated is huge, you can try to compare the number of constraints with it and without it.
Updating the o1js version to the last one is also recommended
the move methods , (left: without `toUpdated` , right: with `toUpdated`)
And maybe try to keep toUpdated while removing other method from ZkProgram
is the constraint different for zkprograms and smart contracts?

I think the limits are the same, but the compilation should give different constraints for them.
You can check the number of constraints for your SmartContract too using analyzeMethods() to compare
You are right , I just ran my move function removing somethings other than the `toUpdated` and it compiled.  _ the problem is definitely with constraint.
Seems like you should simplify your ZkProgram or split it to two. The last o1js is also generates less constraints, so it can help upgrading in edge cases

I ran your script on the heaviest version of my `move` method ( that does all the things)
```
PS C:\Users\rudrak\Desktop\MINA\zkchess\contracts> node build/src/PvPChessProgram/Analyze.js
methods analyzed: 5.449s
method's total size for a PvPChessProgram is 56903 rows (87% of max 65536 rows)
```
How should I split my zkProgram?
@gregor  can you please comment what is the best way to resolve this problem with the  number of constraints

It depends upon how you consume the proofs. If you can create one ZkProgram with the start method and another with the move method, maybe it will help.

You also have many Provable.If, you can calculate in advance the result before generating the proof and just check the result in provable code, probably in different ZkPrograms for different If values.

Please note that you can run later into RSS memory problems with the ZkProgram of that size, so I would recommend to try to generate several proofs in the same worker and see how the RSS memory is being changed:
https://github.com/zkcloudworker/zkcloudworker-lib/blob/main/src/mina.ts#L195
Yeah this is all great advice from @DFST, don't have anything to add

Just a addition,  currently with o1js 0.17.0 ,

I am getting  significant slower compilation in the web version. I suspect the node runs more parallel-ly than the web version.

Can anyone confirm this?

The compilation speed depends upon available memory; when memory is low, the first compilation can take up to 10 minutes. 
We are building zkCloudWorker to handle such cases in the cloud and make web zkApps run fast.
I can disconfirm this, it should be the same amount of parallelism
